t algorithms.\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\n    def analyze_code(self, code):\\n        \\"\\"\\"\\n        Analyzes the provided code for inefficiencies.\\n        :param code: The code to analyze.\\n        :return: A list of inefficiencies found.\\n        \\"\\"\\"\\n        tree = ast.parse(code)\\n        inefficiencies = []\\n        # Example inefficiency check: unused imports\\n        for node in ast.walk(tree):\\n            if isinstance(node, ast.Import) or isinstance(node, ast.ImportFrom):\\n                for alias in node.names:\\n                    if alias.name not in code:\\n                        inefficiencies.append(f\'Unused import: {alias.name}\')\\n        return inefficiencies\\n\\nclass ComplexityVisualizer:\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\n    Visualizes the complexity of the code.\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\n    def visualize_complexity(self, code):\\n        \\"\\"\\"\\n        Visualizes the complexity of the provided code.\\n        :param code: The code to visualize.\\n        :return: A dictionary with complexity metrics.\\n        \\"\\"\\"\\n        tree = ast.parse(code)\\n        cc = radon.complexity.cc_visit(tree)\\n        return {func.name: func.complexity for func in cc}\\n\\nclass SizeEstimator:\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\n    Estimates the size of the code.\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\n    def estimate_size(self, code):\\n        \\"\\"\\"\\n        Estimates the size of the provided code.\\n        :param code: The code to estimate.\\n        :return: The size of the code in lines.\\n        \\"\\"\\"\\n        return len(code.splitlines())\\n\\nclass CodeCoverage:\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\n    Measures the code coverage.\\n    \\"\\"\\"\\n    def measure_coverage(self, test_script, target_script):\\n        \\"\\"\\"\\n        Measures the code coverage of the target script using the test script.\\n        :param test_script: The script containing the tests.\\n        :param target_script: The script to be tested.\\n        :return: A coverage report.\\n        \\"\\"\\"\\n        cov = coverage.Coverage()\\n        cov.start()\\n        exec(open(test_script).read())\\n        cov.stop()\\n        cov.save()\\n        return cov.report()\\n\\n# Example usage\\nif __name__ == \\"__main__\\":\\n    code = \\"\\"\\"\\ndef example_function(x):\\n    if x > 0:\\n        return x * 2\\n    else:\\n        return x / 2\\n\\"\\"\\"\\n    analyzer = CodeAnalyzer()\\n    inefficiencies = analyzer.analyze_code(code)\\n    print(f\'Inefficiencies: {inefficiencies}\')\\n\\n    visualizer = ComplexityVisualizer()\\n    complexity = visualizer.visualize_complexity(code)\\n    print(f\'Complexity: {complexity}\')\\n\\n    estimator = SizeEstimator()\\n    size = estimator.estimate_size(code)\\n    print(f\'Size: {size} lines\')\\n\\n    coverage = CodeCoverage()\\n    report = coverage.measure_coverage(\'test_script.py\', \'target_script.py\')\\n    print(f\'Coverage Report: {report}\')\\n"\n}\n```\n\nThis `solution.py` includes classes for code analysis, complexity visualization, size estimation, and code coverage, as well as an example usage section. Please note that this is a hypothetical example and may need further refinement and testing to meet all the requirements of the MACAO system.', 'continue_simulation': True, 'communications': [], 'total_milestones': 0, 'agent_kpis': {}}, {'iteration': 4, 'task_assignments': {'agent1': 'Based on the task history and the current state, the next task should be to delegate the code to Agent 2 for further modifications and additions of missing functionalities. Since you have already created the initial code framework, it is now appropriate to pass the task to Agent 2, who is better suited for adding missing functions and ensuring all required features are implemented.\n\nHere is the action you should take to delegate the task to Agent 2:\n\n```json\n{\n  "type": "action_function_call",\n  "action_name": "delegate_task",\n  "args": {\n    "agent_name": "agent2",\n    "task_description": "Revise the code for the Multi-Agent Code Analysis and Optimization (MACAO) system by adding missing functionalities and ensuring all required features are implemented.",\n    "file_path": "C:\\\\Users\\\\70454\\\\Desktop\\\\PredictDesign\\\\results\\\\parallel_api_test\\\\runtime_configs\\\\coding\\\\task_14_workspace\\\\solution.py"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis action will delegate the task to Agent 2, who will take over the code and make the necessary modifications and additions. After Agent 2 has completed their revisions, the code will be passed to Agent 3 for further optimization.', 'agent2': 'Given the feedback and the identified issues in the `TaskManager.get_task_order` method, the next logical step is to implement the suggested changes and ensure the code adheres to best practices. Here\'s a step-by-step plan for your next task:\n\n1. **Implement the Suggested Changes**: Update the `get_task_order` method in the `TaskManager` class to correctly handle task dependencies using topological sorting.\n\n2. **Revise the Code**: Ensure the code is well-documented and adheres to best practices.\n\n3. **Call the `give_advice_and_revise` Action**: Get further feedback and improvements.\n\nHere is the updated code with the suggested changes:\n\n```python\n# solution.py\n\n# Existing code (if any)\n\nclass CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer:\n    """\n    Analyzes the efficiency of the code by checking for common inefficiencies such as\n    unused imports, redundant code, and inefficient algorithms.\n    """\n    def analyze_code(self, code):\n        """\n        Analyzes the given code for inefficiencies.\n        :param code: str - The code to be analyzed.\n        :return: dict - A dictionary containing the analysis results.\n        """\n        # Placeholder for actual code analysis logic\n        analysis_results = {\n            \'unused_imports\': False,\n            \'redundant_code\': False,\n            \'inefficient_algorithms\': False\n        }\n        return analysis_results\n\nclass TaskManager:\n    """\n    Manages development tasks with dependencies. It helps in scheduling tasks and\n    ensuring that dependencies are met before a task is executed.\n    """\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.tasks = {}\n\n    def add_task(self, task_id, dependencies=None):\n        """\n        Adds a task to the task manager.\n        :param task_id: str - The unique identifier for the task.\n        :param dependencies: list - A list of task IDs that this task depends on.\n        """\n        if dependencies is None:\n            dependencies = []\n        self.tasks[task_id] = dependencies\n\n    def get_task_order(self):\n        """\n        Returns the order in which tasks should be executed based on their dependencies.\n        :return: list - A list of task IDs in the order they should be executed.\n        """\n        in_degree = {u: 0 for u in self.tasks}\n        for u in self.tasks:\n            for v in self.tasks[u]:\n                in_degree[v] += 1\n        queue = [u for u in in_degree if in_degree[u] == 0]\n        result = []\n        while queue:\n            u = queue.pop(0)\n            result.append(u)\n            for v in self.tasks[u]:\n                in_degree[v] -= 1\n                if in_degree[v] == 0:\n                    queue.append(v)\n        if len(result) == len(self.tasks):\n            return result\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(\'Cycle detected in the task dependencies\')\n\nclass BuildTimeEstimator:\n    """\n    Estimates the build time for the project based on the number of tasks, their complexity,\n    and the efficiency of the code.\n    """\n    def estimate_build_time(self, num_tasks, code_efficiency):\n        """\n        Estimates the build time for the project.\n        :param num_tasks: int - The number of tasks in the project.\n        :param code_efficiency: dict - The code efficiency analysis results.\n        :return: float - The estimated build time in hours.\n        """\n        # Placeholder for actual build time estimation logic\n        efficiency_factor = 1.0\n        if code_efficiency[\'unused_imports\'] or code_efficiency[\'redundant_code\'] or code_efficiency[\'inefficient_algorithms\']:\n            efficiency_factor = 1.5\n        return num_tasks * efficiency_factor * 0.5  # Assuming each task takes 0.5 hours to complete\n\nclass CollaborativeBuildOptimizer:\n    """\n    The main class that integrates code efficiency analysis, task management, and build time estimation.\n    """\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.code_analyzer = CodeEfficiencyAnalyzer()\n        self.task_manager = TaskManager()\n        self.time_estimator = BuildTimeEstimator()\n\n    def optimize_build(self, code, tasks):\n        """\n        Optimizes the build process by analyzing code efficiency, managing tasks, and estimating build time.\n        :param code: str - The code to be analyzed.\n        :param tasks: list - A list of tasks with their dependencies.\n        :return: dict - A dictionary containing the analysis results, task order, and estimated build time.\n        """\n        # Analyze code efficiency\n        code_efficiency = self.code_analyzer.analyze_code(code)\n\n        # Manage tasks\n        for task in tasks:\n            task_id, dependencies = task\n            self.task_manager.add_task(task_id, dependencies)\n        task_order = self.task_manager.get_task_order()\n\n        # Estimate build time\n        num_tasks = len(tasks)\n        estimated_build_time = self.time_estimator.estimate_build_time(num_tasks, code_efficiency)\n\n        # Return results\n        return {\n            \'code_efficiency\': code_efficiency,\n            \'task_order\': task_order,\n            \'estimated_build_time\': estimated_build_time\n        }\n\n# Example usage\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    # Sample code and tasks\n    sample_code = "import os\\nimport sys\\nprint(\'Hello, World!\')"\n    sample_tasks = [\n        (\'task1\', []),\n        (\'task2\', [\'task1\']),\n        (\'task3\', [\'task1\', \'task2\'])\n    ]\n\n    # Initialize CBO\n    cbo = CollaborativeBuildOptimizer()\n\n    # Optimize build\n    results = cbo.optimize_build(sample_code, sample_tasks)\n\n    # Print results\n    print("Code Efficiency Analysis:", results[\'code_efficiency\'])\n    print("Task Order:", results[\'task_order\'])\n    print("Estimated Build Time:", results[\'estimated_build_time\'], "hours")\n```\n\nAfter implementing these changes, you should call the `give_advice_and_revise` action to get further feedback and improvements:\n\n```json\n{\n    "type": "action_function_call",\n    "action_name": "give_advice_and_revise",\n    "args": {\n        "task_description": "Create a system called Multi-Agent Code Analysis and Optimization (MACAO) that integrates code coverage, complexity visualization, and size estimation functionalities into a single, collaborative platform. The system should provide real-time insights and recommendations for efficient teamwork and continuous improvement in the development process.",\n        "model_name": "Qwen/Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct"\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis will ensure that the code is continuously improved and meets the requirements of the MACAO system.', 'agent3': 'Given the task history and the current focus on optimizing the existing code in `solution.py`, the next logical step is to proceed with the `give_advice_and_revise` action as planned. This action will help you provide specific advice and make necessary revisions to the code, aligning with your strengths in optimization and innovation.\n\nHere\'s the detailed plan for the next task:\n\n### Next Task: Optimize the Code\n\n**Objective:** Optimize the existing code in `solution.py` to improve its quality, coverage, complexity, and size estimation functionalities.\n\n**Steps:**\n\n1. **Analyze the Existing Code:**\n   - Review the current implementation in `solution.py`.\n   - Identify areas that can be improved in terms of perf